column168: ETA OF MOTOR VESSEL "DIXIE EXPRESS" HAD BEEN APPROXIMATELY 1600 HRS. 4/1/00.  VESSEL WAS DELAYED DOWNSTREAM AND DID NOT ARRIVE UNTIL 1700 HRS.  NORMAL SHIFT CHANGE FOR TERMINAL PERSONNEL IS 1700 HRS.  THE OPERATOR ON DAY SHIFT (0500 HRS _ 1700 HRS),  JERROD SMITH, FAILED TO ACCOMPANY GAUGER WHEN TANK #4 WAS GAUGED.  THEREFORE, HE DID NOT KNOW WHAT VOLUMN OF PRODUCT WAS IN TANK #4.  WHEN MR. SMITH"S RELIEF, MR. KEVIN YEAGLE, CAME, HE STATED THAT  A GAUGE NEEDED TO BE OBTAINED FROM THE GAUGER SO THAT A FILL SAFE LEVEL COULD BE ESTABLISHED.  AGAIN, MR. SMITH STATED THAT HE DID NOT ACCOMPANY THE GAUGER TO THE TANK.  MR. SMITH ASSUMED THAT MR. YEAGLE WOULD GET IN TOUCH WITH THE GAUGER AND DETERMINE HIS FINDINGS AND ESTABLISH A SAFE FILL LEVEL.  MR. YEAGLE FAILED TO FOLLOW SPECIFIC WRITTEN PROCEDURES FOR OFF-LOADING OF A MOTOR VESSEL.  INFORMATION IS PROVIDED IN ADVANCE OF THE AMOUNT ONBOARD THE VESSEL BEING DELIVERED TO THE FACILITY.  THE GAUGER MEASURES THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THE TANK AND MAKES THIS INFORMATION AVAILABLE TO THE OPERATOR ON DUTY. THIS BREAK DOWN IN COMMUNICATIONS BETWEEN OPERATORS IS THE PRIMARY CAUSATION FACTOR FOR THIS INCIDENT.  IMMEDIATELY UPON DISCOVERY OF THE OVERFILL, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN WAS INITIATED BY THE PERSONNEL ON SITE.  INCIDENT ACTION PLAN WAS IN PLACE WITHIN 2 HOURS OF INCIDENT RELEASE TIME.  ALL LOST PRODUCT SUBSEQUENTLY PICKED UP TO THE SATISFACTION OF REGULATORY AGENCIES ON SCENE.  ADDITIONAL MANAGEMENT EMPHASIS TO BE PLACED ON ADHERENCE TO EXISTING POLICY AND PROCEDURES.
PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE DUST CAP WHEN IT WAS OPENED, SPILLING 4 OUNCES OF PRODUCT.
INSIDE FILL NEW TANK, PLUG LEFT OUT OF BOTTOM OF TANK, STOPPED PUMPING, ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, CHECK PLUMBING BEFORE FILLING.  NO LOSS INTO SOIL OR WATERWAYS.

column168: CARRIER VEHICLE WAS APPROACHING A TRUCK STOP WHEN THE DRIVER WAS ADVISED VIA CB RADIO OF SOMETHING LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER.  HE ENTERED THE TRUCK STOP, PARKED IN A REMOTE AREA AND INVESTIGATED. HE OPENED THE TRAILER, VERIFIED THE LEAK, IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING PACKAGE, THEN CONTACTED THE CARRIER.  CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE MITIGATION OF THE SITUATION.  WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED THEY FOUND A SINGLE DRUM SHIPMENT ON ITS OWN PALLET.  THE DRUM WAS SECURED TO THE TRAILER WALL BUT NOT TO THE PALLET.  DURING TRANSIT, THE PALLET MOVED UNDER THE DRUM.  AT ONE POINT, THE DRUM WAS RESTING ON A WEAK AREA OF THE PALLET.  AT THAT POINT, THE PALLET FAILED UNDER THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUM.  AS A RESULT, SEVERAL NAILS WERE EXPOSED, ONE OF WHICH CONTACTED AND PIERCED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. CONTRACTOR ABSORBED MUCH OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND NEUTRALIZED THE REST, BOTH IN THE TRAILER AND ON THE GROUND.  THEY PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND PUT IT BACK ONTO THE CARRIER'S TRAILER.  THEY TOOK THE WASTE FOR DISPOSAL.  THE VEHICLE THEN CONTINUED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY.

RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK, GATX 61347, APRIL 4, 2000, DETROIT DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0230 HOURS, TUESDAY, APRIL 4, 2000, AT CONRAIL'S NORTH YARD IN DETROIT, MI, A CONRAIL TRAIN CREW DISCOVERED PRODUCT RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 61347 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM PVS CHEMICALS, INC. EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED IT HAD A #165 RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0349 HOURS, REPAIRS MADE BY PVS WHO REPLACED THE RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK.  HERITAGE (AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR) CLEANED THE SPILLED AREA.  THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND OKAYED FOR DESTINATION.

column168: WE DROPPED THE BOX, THE SPILL & BOX WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

THE COURIER WHO TRANSPORTS FREIGHT FROM GRAND FORKS, ND TO DEVILS LAKE, ND (90 MILES) NOTICED A FAINT SMOKEY ODOR WHEN HE HAD ALMOST REACHED HIS DESTINATION.  WHEN HE STOPPED IN THE GRAVEL PARKING LOT NEAR THE GARAGE FACILITY THAT HOUSES THE FEDEX VEHICLES IN DEVILS LAKE AND OPENED HIS REAR FLOOR, HEAVY SMOKE STARTED COMING FROM THIS PACKAGE.  HE THEN PLACED THE BOX ON THE GRAVEL AWAY FROM HIS VEHICLE.  THE COURIER USED THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER ON THE BOX WHEN HE NOTICES SOME FLAMES COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF THE PACKAGE.  THE DEVILS LAKE POLICE DEPT HAPPENED TO BE IN THE AREA AND STOPPED TO OFFER ASSISTANCE AND NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  I BECAME INVOLVED AT THIS POINT WHEN THE GRAND FORKS NORTH DAKOTA STATION MANAGER CALLED ME ABOUT THIS INCIDENT.  NOTIFICATION TO OUR RADIOACTIVE PHYSICIST WAS MADE AND HE IN TURN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, NOTIFIED THE DOT NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AND COMMUNICATED WITH THE NORTH DAKOTA DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH REPRESENTATIVE.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE SOURCE AND THE METAL SHIELDING FOR THIS RADIOACTIVE MOLYBDENUM GENERATOR WAS INTACT.  THE COURIER AND THE PACKAGE WERE CHECKED FOR CONTAMINATION BY THE FIRE DEPT AND NOTHING ABNORMAL WAS NOTED.  WE DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE WAS A BENT EXHAUST PIPE.  THE EXHAUST HEATED THE FLOOR OF THE VAN ENOUGH TO CAUSE COMBUSTION OF THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER BY THE GRAND FORKS DANGEROUS GOODS SPILL SPECIALIST WHO DROVE OUT TO DEVILS LAKE.

column168: THIS WAS A 9 PIECE SHIPMENT OF " FIRE RESCUE SAWS" WHERE ONE OF THE BOXES HAD A SAW THAT WAS USED AND CONTAINED FUEL. THERE WAS NO SPILL, BUT THE FUEL ODOR WAS NOTICEABLE. SINCE FUELS FOR CHAIN SAWS ARE NORMALLY FLAMMABLE, THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER PACKAGING AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS GIVEN TO FEDEX. THE FAA NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT ON 04/07.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: EMPLOYEES OPENED TRAILER DOORS TO UNLOAD WHEN NOTICED TRAILER FLOOR SOAKED WITH BLOOD. EMPLOYEES USED UNIVERSAL PERCAUTIONS UNLOADING TRAILER TO FIND LEAKING CONTAINER. LEAKING CONTAINER WAS FOUND AND EMPLOYEES USED PROPER SPILL RESPONSE PROCEDURES TO REPACKAGE CONTAINER AND CLEAN UP SPILLED BLOOD. GENERATION WILL BE NOTIFIED TO ENSURE THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT DOES NOT REOCCUR.

UNIT PRESENTED FOR LOADING AT CUSTOMER SITE. DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO LEAVE AREA WHILE CUSTOMERS EMPLOYEES LOADED OUR TRAILER. CUSTOMERS EMPLOYEES OVERFILLED TRAILER AND EXCESS PRODUCT FLOWED OUT OF VAPOR RETURN LINE WHICH CUSTOMER HAD FAILED TO HOOKUP TO THEIR RETURN SYSTEM. ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED UPON CUSTOMERS CONCRETE CONTAINMENT PAD AND DISPOSED OF BY SHIPPER. NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER NOTIFIED BY CARRIER REPORT #526528- MS. REDDY. AT 800-424-8802 11:30 HOURS.

column168: OUR UNIT WAS UNLOADING BY USING CARGO PUMP ON TRACTOR. OUR DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THE FITTING ON THE TRACTOR PUMP AND STOPPED UNLOADING REPLACED GASKET AND FITTING AND STOPPED LEAK. APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT, BUT WAS CAUGHT IN CUSTOMERS CONTAINMENT SYSTEM. CUSTOMER WILL HANDLE ANY DISPOSAL REQUIRED.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: CTNS ARRIVED IN GOOD CONDITION. DOCKMAN LOADED CTN ON SIDE (PERPINDICULAR TO DIRECTIONAL ARROWS). CONTENTS BEGAN LEAKING OUT OF CTN. DOCKMAN NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. SUPERVISOR CONTACTED COMPANY HAZMAT REP, AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO WEAR APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE CLOTHING (GLOVES & GLASSES). THEN UPRIGHT CTN, SPREAD ORGANIC SPILL MATERIAL (SAND, CHEM DRY) AND CLEAN SPILL AREA. CTN LEFT IN WELL VENTILATED AREA TO DRY, CAPS TIGHTNED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.

column168: BAGS WERE LOADED ON THE SKID (BY THE SHIPPER) WITHOUT CARDBOARD BETWEEN THE BAGS AND SKID. THE BAGS WERE OVER HANGING THE SIDES OF THE PALLET AND RIPPED. column168: WHILE LOADING FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED ONE CARTON OF PRODUCT. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED IN HARRISBURG OFF TRAILER 261980 AND DURING UNLOADING DOCKWORKER FOUND THAT THERE WAS A LIQUID ON TOP OF ONE OF THE 2 DRUMS ON SKID.  SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND SIX SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR MSDS.  HAZ MATERIAL CLEANUP TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE CLEANUP AND THEY FOUND THAT THE BUNG ON TOP OF ONE DRUM WAS LOOSE AND HAD TO BE TIGHTENED 3/4 OF A TURN TO TIGHTEN. ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES THEN PLACED THE DRUM IN OVERPACK AND HARRISBURG IS AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER ON THE ONE DRUM.
METAL FATIGUE ON VERY BOTTOM WITH A 8 TO 10" CRACK.  PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM TO BE SHIPPED BACK TO US POLYMERS.

ON 04/18/2000, PRO# 779268232 WAS LOADED ON TRL 920336.  WE HAD TWO DOCKWORKERS LOADING THIS TRL AT THE SAME TIME.  THE LEAKAGE WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL THE DRIVER WAS HOOKING UP TO THIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER BROUGHT IT TO MY ATTENTION  AND WE CONTAINED THE LEAKAGE.

SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED IN MECHANICSBURG OFF TRAILER 262052 AND DURING UNLOADING DOCKWORKER FOUND THAT (1) 5 GAL PAIL WAS LEAKING AROUND TOP LOSS OF APP 1/2 PINT OF GLUE.  SHIPMENT WAS OVERPACKED AND WILL BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS

column168: DOCK MAN DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AS HE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN LOADED ON A PALLET WITH THE OTHER THREE CONTAINERS.  THE LOADING TERMINAL FAILED TO PROPERLY BLOCK THE CONTAINERS IN.  DURING TRANSIT ONE OF THE CONTAINERS FELL OFF THE PALLET AND ENDED UP NEXT TO A WOODEN CRATE.  THE CONSTANT FRICTION/RUBBING OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINER AGAINST THE WOODEN CRATE CAUSED A SMALL HOLE IN THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER ALLOWING SOME OF THE LIQUID CONTENTS TO ESCAPE. CONTAINER HELD IN OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.

THIS WAS A COMPLETE SHIPMENT ONE CARTON WITH 4-GLASS QUART SIZE BOTTLES.  EACH BOTTLE HAD A WRAP OF CARDBOARD AROUND THEM.  THE BOTTLES WERE LOOSE WITHIN THE BOX.  THERE WAS SOME STYROFOAM PEANUT IN THE CARTON BUT NOT ENOUGH TO HOLD THE BOTTOM IN PLACE.  THIS WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

DAMAGED FROM FORKLIFT BLADE BY BREAKER ROGER JAMES.

column168: DOCK HAND ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD THE DRUM WITH A FORKLIFT BLADES, NOT USING THE DRUM ATTACHMENT.  THE FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO SPILL INSIDE THE TRAILER. ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL IN THE TRAILER & ON THE MATERIAL ON THE TARMAC AROUND TRAILER.  THE AREA AROUND THE SPILL WAS ROPED OFF, TRAILER DOOR WAS CLOSED, & CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  HAZPAK INC. WAS ALSO, NOTIFIED TO DISPATCH A CONTAINMENT TEAM TO THE TERMINAL. column168: DURING UNLOADING AT TERMINAL FACILITY, PERSONNEL FOUND EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE AROUND SUBJECT DRUM.  THE TRAILER WAS SECURED AND A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR (ACTION RESOURCES) WAS DISPATCHED TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM AND PROVIDE CLEAN-UP/DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER FLOOR. DURING OVERPACKING OF SUBJECT DRUM IT WAS FOUND THAT THE DRUM HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF A SMALL WOOD BLOCK THAT HAD PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  NO STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED AND MITIGATION ACTIVITIES WERE COMPLETED WITHOUT INCIDENT.

A SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING DRUMS AT THE FACILITY WHEN HE NOTICED THAT A 30 GALLON DRUM WAS LEAKING.  3 GALLONS OF THE PETROLEUM NAPHTHA SOLVENT WAS SPILLED IN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SOLVENT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER 30 GALLON DRUM AND THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEAN-UP WITH ABSORBENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: CARGO TANK 925 WAS LOADED WITH PRODUCT.  ONCE LOADED, THE PRODUCT LEAKED AT THE REAR FLANGE FITTING.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT (APPROX. 1 GALLON) WAS PRIMARILY CAPTURED IN A BUCKET THAT WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAKING FITTING.  A MINUTE AMOUNT ACTUALLY LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. A REPAIR SERVICE WAS DISPATCHED TO REPAIR THE LEAKING FITTING ON THE TANK TRAILER.  THE FITTING WAS REPAIRED BY TIGHTENING THE LOOSE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE FITTING.  ONCE REPAIRED, THE PRODUCT RELEASE ENDED, AND A "NITROGEN BLANKET" WAS PLACED ON TOP ON THE MATERIAL IN THE TANK TRAILER.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT THAT WAS CAPTURED IN THE BUCKET WAS GIVEN BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL ACCORDING TO THEIR PLANT RULES.  THE MINUTE AMOUNT RELEASED ON THE GROUND WAS ALSO CLEANED-UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT THEIR FACILITY.

WHILE UNLOADING AT THE TERMINAL, A 1 GALLON CAN IN A CARTON OF 4 CANS WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED ON THE DOCK.  APPARENTLY THE CAN WAS DAMAGED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY THE SHIPPING CARTON.  THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PLACED THE ENTIRE CARTON INTO A 5 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  AN MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE LOADING, ONE LEAKING, ONE HUNDRED AND SIXTY LITER CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY ONE HUNDRED AND TWENTY LITERS WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CYLINDER WAS DUE TO A FAULTY RELIEF VALVE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM RELIEVED THE PRESSURE ON THE VALVE AND PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION. THE REMAINING THREE CYLINDERS WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TWO DAMAGED, FIVE POUND BAGS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. column168: FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS LOADING A "SHORT" PALLET BEHIND SAID DAMAGED DRUM ALREADY STAGED IN TRAILER.  FORKLIFT BLADES WERE EXTENDED BEYOND THE PALLET HE WAS LOADING AND TOO HIGH OFF THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  WHEN FORKLIFT OPERATOR WENT TO STAGE SAID PALLET BEHIND THIS DRUM HE STRUCK THE DRUM WITH THE FORKBLADE PUNCTURING IT.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS' SIDE AND WAS REPAIRED WITH PUTTY AND IS AWAITING DISPOSITION.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS RELATIVELY NEW AND WAS GIVEN A CORRECTIVE INTERVIEW AND SHOWN THE IMPORTANCE AND PROPER WAY TO LOAD FREIGHT UNDER THESE CIRCUMSTANCES.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER, UNLOADED NOTICED SMALL SEEPAGE COMING FROM BOTTOM OF SAID DRUM.  SEEPAGE WAS COMING FROM WELD/SEAM AT BOTTOM OF DRUM. column42: COATING SOLUTION ( INCLUDES SURFACE TREATMENTS OR COATINGS USED FOR INDUSTRIAL OR OTHER PURPOSES SUCH AS VEHICLE UNDERCOATING, DRUM OR BARREL LINING )
column168: WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT THE UNLOADER NOTICED A WET SPOT NEAR THE CLOSURE ON TOP OF THE PAIL.  HE TRIED TO TIGHTEN IT BY HAND, HOWEVER THE CLOSURE CONTINUED TO SEEP AFTER ATTEMPT.  THE PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

OUR DELIVERY DRIVER WAS MAKING THIS DELIVERY.  UPON REMOVING DRUMS FROM TRAILER WITH A DRUM CART, IT WAS NOTICED LEAKING AT THE TOP SEAM WHEN DRIVER STARTED TO TILT BACK ON DRUM CART.  SMALL AMOUNT THAT LEAKED OUT WAS WIPED UP AND DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  NOT EXACTLY SURE WHAT CONTRIBUTED TO LEAKAGE, BUT FEEL IT WAS EITHER CAUSED BY THE DRUM "PICKER" ATTACHMENT WHEN IT WAS ORIGINALLY LOADED AT THE TERMINAL OR BY ANOTHER DRUM WHEN IT WAS LOADED UP AGAINST IT.

WHEN OUR PICKUP DRIVER AS MAKING PICKUP FROM SAID HE NOTICED THAT ONE OF THE GAYLORDS HAD A HOLE IN IT, BUT WAS NOT LEAKING ANYTHING DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE GAYLORD WAS WRAPPED WITH "STRETCH WRAP". UPON UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT AT TERMINAL IT AS NOTICED THAT A VERY SMALL AMOUNT HAD INDEED LEAKED OUT ONTO TRAILER FLOOR.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND WE HELD SHIPMENT UNTIL THE SHIPPER SENT A OVERPACK FOR THIS SHIPMENT.  SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO OVERPACK AND SHIPPED TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE AS PER INSTRUCTED.  ORIGINAL PICKUP DRIVER WAS GIVEN A VERBAL CORRECTIVE INTERVIEW AND INSTRUCTED NEVER TO ACCEPT A SHIPMENT IN THIS CONDITION.

DOCKWORKER WAS SEPARATING A PALLET OF MIXED FREIGHT.  WHILE UNLOADING HE WAS REMOVING THE PLASTIC STRETCH WRAP AS HE REMOVED PACKAGES.  HE WAS PULLING BACK THE STRETCH WRAP  AND SOME LIQUID WENT INTO HIS EYE CAUSING A BURNING SENSATION.  HIS EYES WERE FLUSHED WITH  EYE WASH SOLUTION AND HE WAS TAKEN TO DOCTOR FOR FURTHER EXAMINATION.  UPON EXAMINING THE FREIGHT IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE PAILS CONTAINING THIS SODIUM HYDROXIDE HAD A LOOSE LID AND IT HAD LEAKED IN AND ONTO THE STRETCH WRAP.  WHEN THE DOCK WORKER PULLED TO REMOVE THE WRAP IT SUBSEQUENTLY WENT INTO HIS EYES. FORTUNATELY THERE WAS NO  PERMANENT DAMAGE, JUST AN IRRITATION.  THE LOOSE LID WAS TIGHTENED ON PAIL AND WAS SHIPPED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.

WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER AT TERMINAL A SMALL WET SPOT WAS NOTICED UNDER DRUM.  UPON EXAMINATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A SEAM ON THE DRUM WAS SLIGHTLY CRACKED CAUSING LEAKAGE.  IT MUST HAVE BEEN LIKE THIS WHEN LOADED AT SHIPPER BECAUSE THERE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED IN POLY RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

WHILE PUMPING COMMODITY INTO RAILCAR, RAIL CAR OVERFILLED CAUSING MATERIAL TO COME OUT OF VENT OF CAR. OVERFILL WAS DETECTED IMMEDIATELY AND RAIL CAR VALVE WAS CLOSED & PUMP SHUT DOWN. SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS. SPILLAGE WAS LIMITED TO PAVED AREA AT SITE OF RAIL CAR. FUTURE LOADING TO BE MONITORED VISUALLY TO ENSURE TANK CARS ARE NOT OVERFILLED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 HOURS ON APRIL 20, 2000, THE FILL OPERATOR AT THE GENEVA STEEL COKE PLANT BY PRODUCTS FACILITY SPILLED 30 GALLONS OF COAL CAR DISTILLATE (I.E., LIGHT OIL) WHICH CONTAINED 162 LBS OF BENZENE WHILE LOADING RAIL TANK CAR UTLX642930. THERE WERE NO PERSONNEL INJURIES OR EQUIPMENT DAMAGE. MOST OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL FLASHED-OFF INTO THE AIR AND THE SMALL AMOUNT OF IMPACTED SOIL, TO THE EXTENT POSSIBLE WAS PLACED IN A HAZARDOUS WASTE DRUM AT A SATELLITE ACCUMULATION AREA. THE CAUSE OF THE OVERFILL RELEASE WAS DETERMINED TO BE AN OVER SIGHT BY AN OPERATOR TO ESTIMATE THE RESIDUAL VOLUME BEFORE FILLING THE RAIL TANKER CAR FULL OF COAL TAR DISTILLATE. TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF SUCH A RELEASE, THE SAFE JOB PROCEDURES WAS MODIFIED AND THE FILL OPERATOR WAS RE-INSTRUCTED ON ESTABLISHED PROCEDURES. THE FILL OPERATOR ALSO RECEIVED A WRITTEN VIOLATION NOTICE OF ESTABLISHED PROCEDURES.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE FOR THE FACILITY WAS DRILLING HOLES INTO THE TRAILER FOR NEW PLACARDS WHEN HE DRILLED THROUGH THE TRAILER'S SIDE AND THROUGH THE WALL OF A TRANSFORMER CONTAINING 430 PPM POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYL OIL.  15 GALLONS OF THE OIL SPILLED ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 110 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE CONTAMINATED TRAILER, CONTAINERS, AND PARKING LOT WERE DOUBLE WASHED WITH A PCB ABSORBENT SOLVENT, 100% SOLVENT ON THE FIRST WASH AND 50% SOLVENT ON THE SECOND.  THIS SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 2,700 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 806 GENESSEE, IN KANSAS CITY, MO FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INCIDENT WAS COUNSELED ON THE PROPER USE AND HANDLING OF POWER TOOLS.

DEFECTIVE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, GATX 95104, APRIL 25, 2000 DETROIT DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1635 HOURS, TUESDAY, APRIL 25, 2000, IN TRENTON, MICHIGAN, THE TRENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED OUT BY LOCAL RESIDENTS TO RESPOND TO AN ODOR FROM AN UNKNOWN SOURCE.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THE TRENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT REVEALED THE ODOR WAS EMANATING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 95104 RESIDUE:  LAST CONTAINED METHYL MERCAPTAN (METHYL MERCAPTAN GAS).  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  CANADIAN NATIONAL RAILROAD AND CONRAIL'S TRAINMASTER ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND SUSPECTED A VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0015 HOURS, APRIL 26, 2000, IT CORPORATION, AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND APPLIED MIDLAND CAPPING TO THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0115 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS CONTAINED.  THE TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, ELF ATO CHEM, TRENTON, MICHIGAN.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS REPLACED BY THE SHIPPER AND WILL BE EXAMINED TO DETERMINE THE EXACT CAUSE.
THE DRIVER OVERFILLED THE TANK DUE TO ASSUMING THE TANK WAS AN 8000 GALLON TANK.  THE TANK SIZE WAS ACTUALLY 6000 GALLONS CAPACITY.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS AN INTER-PLANT TRANSFER OF LIQUID FROM DRUMS TO TANKER.  AFTER  VACUUMING 13 DRUMS OF APPROXIMATELY 500 TOTAL GALLONS, A CHEMICAL REACTION OCCURRED IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A VAPOR OF STEAM, NITROGEN AND AMMONIA GAS TO ESCAPE FROM THE VACUUM PUMP DUE TO AN INCREASE IN PRESSURE IN THE TANK FROM THE CHEMICAL REACTION.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE VACUUM AND ALLOWED TO PRESSURE TO VENT THROUGH A 2" VAC LINE.  THE SITE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE SITE FIRE DEPT WHO HOSED DOWN THE TRAILER TO COOL THE TANK UNTIL THE REACTION HAD SUBSIDED.  THE CUSTOMER (DUPONT) IS REVIEWING THEIR SAMPLING AND COMINGLING PROCEDURES FOR ON-SITE VACUUMING.

DRIVER NOTICED AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM THE CARGO AREA OF TRUCK WHILE TRAVELING NORTH ON SR101. HE IMMEDIATELY TURNED LEFT ONTO COUNTY ROAD 38 TO GET OFF THE MAIN HIGHWAY. HE OPENED THE CARGO DOOR AND DETERMINED HE HAD A LEAKING MINIBULK OF ZIN TECH. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS OFFICE AND BEGAN CLEAN UP OF CARGO AREA WITH ABSORBANTS. THE STATE HIGHWAY PATROL, THE TIFFIN FIRE CHIEF AND THE TOWNSHIP FIRE CHIEF WAS IN DIRECT CONTACT WITH OUR OFFICE DURING THIS RELEASE. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NRC,EPA,LEPC AND PUCO. EPA OFFICER, ED POLIDA (BOWLING GREEN) WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE. AN MSDS WAS PROVIDED. THE OFFICER DETERMINED THAT SINCE THE SPILL WAS EVAPORATING RAPIDLY AND THAT IT POSED NO ENVIRONMENTAL THREAT, NO CLEANUP WOULD BE NECESSARY. PUCO HAZMAT SPECIALIST, KELLY HEDGLIN, INSPECTED THE TANK, TRUCK AND INTERVIEWED THE DRIVER.

WHILE UNLOADING, A BOX WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED BY SHRINK WRAP THAT WAS APPLIED TO TIGHT. THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG. THE BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A LOOSE BUNG. THE BUNG COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED. THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: DRIVER PULLED OFF INTO A REST AREA OFF INTERSTATE 40 IN CAMDEN TN WHEN THE DRIVER GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND WALKED AROUND THE TRAILER HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS SOME PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER GOT A BUCKET AND PLACED IT UNDER THE LEAKING VALVE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE WELD AROUND THE VALVE HAD A CRACK IN IT, THIS IS WHAT CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO LEAK.

VACUUM TRAILER #1 WAS LOADING MATERIAL TO ANOTHER TANK CAR, AIR BUBBLE GOT IN TANK CAR #2 PUSHING MATERIAL OUT OF THE DOME LID TAH WAS LOOSENED TO VENT. MATERIAL GOT ON ASPHALT IN PHILLIPS CHEMICAL PROPERTY, TXI TRANSPORTATION AND PHILLIPS CHEM. PERSONNEL THOROUGHLY CLEANED SPILL & PHILLIPS KEPT SPILLED MATERIAL FOR PROPER MANAGEMENT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT THE TERMINAL TWO 20 POUNDS PLASTIC BAGS WERE FOUND DAMAGED. APPARENTLY THE BAGS WERE DAMAGED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZ MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP BY SWEEPING UP THE FREE PRODUCT. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED BAGS WERE REPAIRED AND WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. AN MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING ONE LEAKING FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS FOUND IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF TEASPOON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP WITH A RAG, GLOVES AND A PLASTIC BAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS AND FREIGHT BILL WERE REQUESTED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING ONE, ONE GALLON CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED BY A DOCK WORKER AT THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. THE HARDEN PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, ALONG WITH THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE BUNG ON THE DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 5 GALLON FIBER DRUM. THE 5 GALLON FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. WHILE UNLOADING. TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED AN ODOR IN THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM TWO CYLINDERS OF RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, CORROSIVE N.O.S., LOCATED AT THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY A HALF POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE VALVES ON THE CYLINDER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED LEVEL C PROTECTION TO PLACE THE CYLINDERS INTO AN ISOLATION TRAILER. A THIRD UNAFFECTED CYLINDER IN THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN THE ISOLATION TRAILER AS WELL. THEY WILL BE HELD FOR 48 HOURS AND THEN FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE PROTECTIVE GEAR WAS PLACED INTO A 25 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. column168: NC 465307 A BOXCAR UNDER SEAL WAS OBSERVED WITH SMOKE COMING FROM THE BOXCAR BY THE CREW OF A PASSING TRAIN. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD BY EVACUATING THE SURROUNDING COMMUNITY. LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS, THE SHIPPER AND ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST WERE NOTIFIED. EVACUATION OF THE PUBLIC WAS IMPLEMENTED. AFTER CONSULTATION WITH AUTHORITIES AND THE SHIPPER, THE CAR WAS MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE TO A SAFER MORE ISOLATED AREA WHERE EMERGENCY OPERATIONS WERE CONDUCTED TO CONTROL PRODUCT RELEASE AND MITIGATE ANY ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE. 32 BINS CONTAINING THE PRODUCT WERE REMOVED FROM THE CAR OPENED AND THE PRODUCT NEUTRALIZED ON SITE USING ACCEPTED SCIENTIFIC STANDARDS AND PRACTICES. ALL WASTE MATERIAL GENERATED WAS PROPERLY CONTAINED AND DISPOSED OF. THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT AND THE ACTUAL NUMBER OF BINS WHICH FAILED IN LIKE MANNER REMAINS UNDER INVESTIGATION. INSPECTION OF THE CAR EVIDENCES NO MISHANDLING OF THE CAR BY THE RAILCAR DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE INITIAL NUMBER OF EVACUEES (1,000) IS AN ESTIMATED BASED ON FIGURES BY LOCAL EMERGENCY REPONDERS. THE INITIAL EVACUATION LASTED ABOUT 3 HOURS. FIVE RESIDENCES IN THE AREA WHERE THE CAR WAS MOVED FOR EMERGENCY HANDLING (ABOUT ONE AND ONE-HALF MILES SOUTH OF THE YARD) WERE EVACUATED FOR 4 DAYS. AN ESTIMATED 40 PEOPLE WERE TREATED AND RELEASED FROM LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITIES AFTER BEING EXAMINED FOR ALLEGED EXPOSURE TO FUMES GENERATED BY THE BURNING MATERIAL. THE EXTENT OF DAMAGES SUFFERED REFERRED TO IN ITEMS 23.A THROUGH 23.E ABOVE MAY INCREASE. THE ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE WAS MINIMAL WITH NO IMPACT TO WATER.

column168: OUR UNIT WAS TRAVELING N.E. ON LOOP 375, HE EXITED AT RAILROAD DRIVE.  BASED ON THE EVIDENCE OF MY INVESTIGATION, THE DRIVER STARTED INTO THE CURVE GOING TOO FAST.  I THINK HE GOT ON HIS BRAKES VERY HARD, THEN GOT BACK OFF OF THEM.  AS HE GOT ABOUT 1/2 TO 3/4 AROUND THE CURVE (STILL GOING TOO FAST) THE SURGE AND SLOSH FACTOR CLIMBED THE WALLS OF THE TANK ROLLING THE UNIT OVER ONTO IT'S LEFT SIDE AND COMING TO REST UPSIDE DOWN.  THERE ARE 2 PRIMARY CONTRIBUTING FACTORS, 1ST IS THE UNITS SPEED, 2ND THE TRAILER WAS A 9500 GALLON CAP. TRAILER, THE DRIVER HAD ONLY LOADED 7300 GALLONS OF DIESEL.  THE DOWNLOADED COMPARTMENTS CONTRIBUTED TO AN EXCESSIVE AMOUNT OF SLOSH AND SURGE.

PRODUCT WAS NOT PROTECTED BY DUNNAGE OR PLYWOOD.  DOUBLED STACKED SKID OF FRT SLID BACKWARDS IN TRANSIT CAUSING THE PAIL TO BE CRUSHED AND TEAR.  CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.  NO DAMAGE TO OTHER FRT OR TRAILER AS THE GLUE DRIED QUICKLY UPON RELEASE FROM CONTAINER.

WHEN DIESEL STARTED OVERFILLING HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN SYSTEM, BUT LOST 61 GALLONS THAT WENT INTO M R C RECOVERY SYSTEM.  MONTANA REFINERY EMPLOYEE INFORMED DRIVER THAT SCULLY SYSTEM WASN'T WORKING RIGHT SO HAD IT BY PASSED.

column168: RAIL CAR, MP722393, COVERED HOPPER LD AMMONIUM NITRATE, SPILLED 500 LBS OF PRODUCT ON THE HUMP IN CSXT'S RAIL YARD AT LOUISVILLE, KY. THE TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT EXPLAINED THE CAR WAS HUNG UP ON THE HUMP & ANOTHER CAR STRUCK IT.  THE IMPACT JARRED ONE OF THE BOTTOM GATES OPEN SLIGHTLY & RELEASED THE PRODUCT.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED & VACCUMED UP THE PRODUCT PLACING THE MATERIAL INTO 15, 55 GAL DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE TEMPORARILY STORED AT THE YARD.  THE PRODUCT WAS SALVAGED BY A FARMER FOR USE AS A FERTILIZER ON HIS PASTURES.

column168: TRAIN C74809 DERAILED FOUR CARS AT MILEPOST 7.6 OF THE STONEY CREEK BRANCH, ALBANY DIVISION.  TWO TANK CARS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT.  THE FIRST TANK CAR UCLX 20092, CONTAINED TETRACHLOROETHYLENE, A 6.1 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS CAR WAS OFF ITS WHEELS AND LEANING, WITH NO LEAKAGE OF ITS CONTENTS.  THE SECOND TANK CAR MOBX 26010, CONTAINED LUBRICATING OIL, A NON-REGULATED MATERIAL.  THE CAR CONTAINING LUBE OIL LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF OIL FROM THE PACKING GLAND OF THE STUFFING BOX OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE DERAILMENT SITE.  AS A PRECAUTION, THE LOCAL INCIDENT COMMANDER EVACUATED APPROXIMATELY 30 PERSONS FROM AN ADJACENT APARTMENT COMPLEX.  THE EVACUATION WAS IN A PLACE FROM APPROXIMATELY 0820 HOURS TO 1053 HOURS.  THE OTHER CARS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT WERE 1) A BOX CAR LOADED WITH PAPER AND 2) A FLAT CAR LOADED WITH LUMBER.  ALL CARS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT WERE SUCCESSFULLY RERAILED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: AT 0730 ON APRIL 15TH, THE DRIVER ARRIVED TO DELIVER PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMER TANK LOCATED OFF ROUTE 12 IN CHESTERTON, IN.  AFTER OFF-LOADING 125,000 CUBIC FEET (APPROXIMATELY 125 GALLONS), THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON THE TRAILER LIFTED WHEN THE CARGO TANK PRESSURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 120 PSIG (CARGO TANK RATED FOR 150 PSIG). THE VENTING HYDROGEN IGNITED.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED THE CARGO TANK TRAILER AND THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK AND THEN CALLED 911.  USING A SOFTWARE CALLED CAMEO TO DETERMINE EMERGENCY RESPONSE DISTANCES, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED 300 CITIZENS, SHUTDOWN THE SOUTH SHORE LINE (COMMUTER RAIL) AND CLOSED US HIGHWAY 12 FOR 2 HOURS.
THE THREADS ON A FITTING ON CUSTOMER FILL LINE WERE WORN AND FITTING LEAKED.  ALL PRODUCT WENT INTO CONTAINED AREA.
DRIVER FLIPPED LATCH DOWN TO CLOSE INTERNAL VALVE AFTER TAKING SAMPLE, BUT INTERNAL DID NOT COMPLETELY CLOSE AND WHEN DRIVER OPENED EXTERNAL PRODUCT CAME OUT USED SPILL PADS TO CLEAN UP.
VALVE ON TOP OF CUSTOMER TANK LEAKING AROUND THE ELBOW WASHED DOWN CUSTOMER DRAIN.
UNLOADING INTO CUSTOMER TANK.  PRODUCT FOAMED OUT OF TANK FROM THE VENT.  PRODUCT HOSE DOWN CUSTOMER DRAIN.
AFTER UNLOADING DRIVER NOTICED A DRIP COMING FROM A PUMP ON CUSTOMER TANK.  MAINTENANCE REPAIRED.  SPILL CLEANED UP WITH SPILL PADS.

ON APRIL 25TH AT 8:10am, TANK CAR WAS BEING PREPARED TO UNLOAD PRODUCT INTO TANKER TRUCK.  WHILE APPLYING AIR PRESSURE TO TANK CAR FOR UNLOADING, LOADER NOTICED A "BEAD" OF PRODUCT APPEARING ON THE WELDED SEAM OF THE LEFT CENTER SECTION OF THE TANK CAR.  AIR PRESSURE WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED, AND SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.  NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK CAR, OTHER THAN THE SMALL "BEAD" THAT HAD APPEARED ON THE WELD WHEN AIR PRESSURE WAS APPLIED.  TANK CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY UNLOADED VIA PUMP DURING SEVERAL TRUCK LOADS IN THE FOLLOWING WEEK.  TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED BY THE FRA, AND EXEMPTION WAS GRANTED FOR MOVEMENT OF THE EMPTY TANKS CAR TO TEXAS TANKCAR WORKS IN PLUM, TEXAS.  TANK CAR WAS ALSO INSPECTED BY RAILROAD MECHANICAL SHOP, AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF DAMAGE IN TRANSIT THAT CAUSED THE INCIDENT.  THE MOST PROBABLE CAUSE IS A TEAR OR DEFECT IN THE RUBBER LINING.
PLASTIC SEALS ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM HAD CRACKED OPEN.  ALLOWING SOME OF THE PRODUCT TO SEEP ONTO THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WASHED ON DOCK UNTIL SHIPPER COULD REPAIR VALVE.

THE CAM LOCK CAME LOOSE FROM HE TRAILER SPILLING ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF CAUSTIC SODA OVER A 2 MILE RADIUS.  ONCE THE DRIVER REALIZED WHAT HAPPENED, HE CALLED THE OFFICE MANAGER.  THE WASHINGTON STATE DOT CAME TO THE LOCATION FOR ROAD CONTROL WHILE COWLITZ CLEAN SWEEP INC. CLEANED THE SPILL.  THE ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS ARE TRAINING VIA SAFETY VIDEO'S MEETINGS AND BULLETINS.
PIPE LEADING TO THE TANK CRACKED HESS CORP CLEANED.

A SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING DOUBLE STACKED PALLETS OF WASTE AT A TEN STORAGE FACILITY'S WAREHOUSE. A 15 GALLON DRUM ON THE TOP PALLET FELL TO THE GROUND POPPING OFF IT'S LID. 14 GALLONS OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE SOLUTION INSIDE THE DRUM SPILLED INTO A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA WHICH WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND THE WASTE MATERIAL CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 140 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL TO A SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE IN HEBRON, OH FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER SECURING OF DRUM ON PALLET AND FORKLIFT HANDLING TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE TRUCK SENT TO ITS DESTINATION FACILITY. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY  575 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, TO A SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT RT 322 AND I-295 IN BRIDGEPORT, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE SAFETY KLEEN DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER INSPECTION OF A LOAD BEFORE TRANSPORTATION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: A CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC (CHESI) VAN TRAILER CONTAINING TWO (2) 320 GALLON TOTE TANKS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM HOWMET TURBINE CORPORATION AT 1 HOWMET DRIVE HAMPTON VA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE INC, (CHBI) LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL ST IN BALTIMORE MD TO CONDUCT AN IN TRANSIT TRUCK TO TRUCK TRANSFER. WHEN THE VEHICLE ARRIVED OUTSIDE THE FACILITY GATE, THE DRIVER OBSERVED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE VAN TRAILER. HE WAS IMMEDIATELY DIRECTED TO MOVE THE TRUCK ONTO A SPILL PAD LOCATED ON CHBI PROPERTY. CHBI PERSONNEL INITIATED CLEANUP OPERATIONS OUTSIDE THE GATE AND ON THE SPILL PAD BY APPLYING LIME AND SODA ASH TO THE SPILL AREAS. APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS WAS DISCHARGED OUTSIDE THE GATE. WHEN THE SPILL  AREAS WERE CLEANED, BOTH TOTE TANKS WERE REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE;  A SIGNIFICANT CRACK WAS OBSERVED IN THE RIGHT REAR CORNER OF THE DAMAGED TOTE. THE REMAINING MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM THE DAMAGED TOTE. THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE CRACK IS NOT KNOWN TO CHESI. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION THE DRIVER INSPECTED BOTH CONTAINERS FOR INTEGRITY AND LEAKAGE AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF EITHER. CHESI PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CONTINUE INSPECTING ALL CONTAINERS PRIOR TO ACCEPTING THEM FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DRIVER CALLED TO REPORT HE WAS AT THE FUEL ISLAND OF A TRUCK STOP. ABOUT 1/2 PINT OF SOMETHING LEAKED FROM HIS TRAILER. IT HAS A STRONG ODOR. AFTER VIEWING THE VARIOUS SHIPMENTS IN THE LOAD, HAZMAT INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO MOVE TO A REMOTE AREA OF THE TRUCK STOP AND AWAIT ASSISTANCE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT (NORTH CALLAWAY FIRE PROTECTION DISTRICT) WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. THEY REMAINED ON LOCATION FOR THE DURATION OF THE CLEAN UP. CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR FROM ST. LOUIS, MO., ABOUT TWO HOURS DISTANT. THEY WERE THE CLOSET AVAILABLE CONTRACTOR WHO COULD HANDLE EPICHLOROHYDRIN, WHAT WAS BELIEVED TO BE LEAKING. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED; THEY RECOMMENDED THAT THE TRAILER DOORS BE KEPT CLOSED UNTIL THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVES. PERSONNEL FROM THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT 1600. AFTER MAKING ENTRY THEY WERE ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT A DRUM OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN IN THE SECOND ROW FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING AT ITS BOTTOM. A SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE STRESSED THAT ONLY PERSONNEL IN APPROPRIATE PPE SHOULD BE INVOLVED IN THE TRANSFER AND MITIGATION EFFORTS. 2150 A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE CONTRACTOR CALLED TO REPORT THAT THE CLEAN UP IS ESSENTIALLY COMPLETED. THE BAD DRUM HAS BEEN LOCATED. IT HAS A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM HEAD RUNNING FROM THE CHIME IN TOWARD THE CENTER OF THE HEAD. THERE IS NO VISIBLE REASON FOR IT OTHER THAN A DESIGN AND/OR MANUFACTURING DEFECT. THE CONTRACTOR HAS GOTTEN SEVERAL GOOD PHOTOS OF IT. THEY PUT THE LEAKING DRUM UPSIDE DOWN INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THEY CLEANED UP WHAT HAD SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, GENERATING ONLY FIVE GALLON PAIL OF WASTE MATERIALS. THE OVERPACK DRUM CONTAINING THE LEAKING DRUM WITH PRODUCT IN IT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD AT THE CARRIER'S MAIN FACILITY FOR REVIEW. THE CARRIER EXPERIENCED A SIMILAR INCIDENT ON 7/22/99. EPICHLOROHYDRIN IN DRUMS FROM THE SAME CZECHOSLOVAKIAN DRUM MANUFACTURER BUT SHIPPED BY DIFFERENT SHIPPER WERE INVOLVED. IN BOTH CASES THE US REPRESENTATIVE OF THE DRUM MANUFACTURER WAS CONTACTED. WE NOTE THAT THESE DRUMS DO NOT HAVE STIFFENING RINGS AT THEIR BOTTOMS.

column168: DRIVER CALLED THE CARRIER TO REPORT THAT HE HAD LEAKAGE FROM A TOTE. SOME OF THE LIQUID WAS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND SOME OF THAT HAD RUN FROM THE RIGHT REAR CORNER OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE PAVEMENT. AT DIRECTION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, THE DRIVER PLACED SPILL KIT PADS ON THE GROUND UNDER THE TRAILER CORNER, WITH AN ABSORBENT SOCK AROUND THE PADS. HE STATED THAT THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE AT THE TOP OF THE TOTE, POSSIBLY COMING FROM THE FILL CAP. HE PHOTOGRAPHED THE SCENE, THEN ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE CAP. THE CAP WOULD NOT TURN, EITHER TO TIGHTEN OR LOOSEN. PRESUMABLY IT WAS CROSS-THREADED. THE DRIVER PLACED SOME MORE PADS AND SOCK AROUND THE CAP, RETRIEVED THE CLEANUP MATERIALS FROM THE PAVEMENT AND PUT THEM INTO A PLASTIC BAG. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO A NEARBY TRUCK STOP AND RECHECKED THE TOTE. HE DID NOT SEE ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE, BUT HE ACQUIRED AND PUT SOME OIL DRY ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. HE CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE TOTE, GIVING A CLEAR RECEIPT FOR IT. THE DRIVER SWEPT UP THE OIL DRY AND ADDED IT TO THE BAG OF SPILL KIT MATERIALS. HE DROPPED IT AT THE NEXT FACILITY OF THE CARRIER THAT HE PASSED.

column168: DRIVER CALLED THE CARRIER FROM A TRUCK STOP STATING HE HAD LIQUID RUNNING FROM THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. HE HAD BEEN INFORMED OF THE LEAK BY THE TRUCK STOP MANAGEMENT. THE DRIVER PARKED THE UNIT IN AN AREA FREE OF STORM SEWERS. THE DRIVER AND A TRUCK STOP EMPLOYEE DEPLOYED ABSORBENT AROUND THE SPILL AND ISOLATED THE TRAILER. TRUCK STOP MANAGEMENT NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPT. THE CARRIER NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER OF THE INCIDENT. THE SHIPPER CONTRACTED A RESPONSE TEAM TO MITIGATE THE INCIDENT. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED. A LARGE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN LOADED BY THE SHIPPER AND DIVIDED FOR WEIGHT BALANCE. THE PORTION OF THE LOAD TOWARDS THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER HAD BEEN SECURED WITH A SINGLE STRAP. THE DRIVER STATED THAT WHILE IN TRANSIT IT WAS NECESSARY MAKE A QUICK STOP IN TRAFFIC. THE FREIGHT SHIFTED FORWARD PULLING A SECTION OF LOGISTIC RAIL OUT OF THE WALL. ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS THEN PUNCTURED BY A PROTRUDING PIECE OF THE RAIL CAUSING A RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM, DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND THE SURROUNDING AREA.

DRIVER REPORTS THAT HE HAND CARRIED TWO 5-GALLON PAILS INTO THE BUILDING, COMPLETED AN INSIDE DELIVERY AND RECEIVED A CLEAR DELIVERY RECEIPT FOR THEM. WHEN HE WALKED OUTSIDE HE FELT WETNESS ON THE SIDES OF BOTH OF HIS LEGS. BOTH PANT LEGS HAVE SOME LIQUID ON THEM. DRIVER STATES THAT HE WENT BACK INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S BUILDING TO A MEN'S ROOM AND RINSED HIS LEGS OFF THOROUGHLY. HAZMAT REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE SHIPPER VIA NORMAL REPORTING CHANNELS. SHIPPER'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST REQUESTED THAT A CONFERENCE CALL BE ESTABLISHED BETWEEN THE DRIVER, HIMSELF AND THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST. DURING THE CALL THE SHIPPER'S SPECIALISTS, AFTER ESTABLISHING THAT THE DRIVER HAD INDEED BECOME EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT, INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER IN NO UNCERTAIN TERMS TO ACQUIRE A CLEAN PAIR OF PANTS, TO RINSE HIMSELF AGAIN AND TO PUT THE SOILED PANTS INTO A PLASTIC BAG. HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO CARRY THEM IN THE TRAILER RATHER THAN IN THE TRACTOR. THE SHIPPER'S SPECIALIST ALSO GAVE THE DRIVER ADVICE ON WHAT SYMPTOMS OF ILLNESS TO BE ALERT FOR, AND WHAT TO DO IN THE EVENT THAT ANY SHOULD APPEAR. DRIVER STATED THAT HE FELT FINE; THAT HE WAS NOT PRESENTING ANY OF THE DESCRIBED SYMPTOMS BUT WOULD REPORT ANY THAT BECOME APPARENT IN THE FUTURE. CARRIER'S SPECIALIST REINFORCED THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS AND ASSURED ITSELF THAT THEY WERE FOLLOWED. AS OF THE DATE OF THIS REPORT (5/25/00), THE DRIVER HAS NOT REPORTED ANY ILL EFFECTS FROM THE OCCURRENCE.

column168: PURITY PRODUCTS WAS CONTRACTED TO PICK-UP A LOAD AT BUCKMANS, INC. LOCATED IN PERKIOMENVILLE, PA TO BE TRANSPORTED TO AMATO INDUSTRIES LOCATED IN SILVER SPRINGS, MD BY K.W. WHILE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 476 IN PENNSYLVANIA JUST PRIOR TO INTERSTATE 95(S), A POLICE OFFICER (UNSURE IF STATE OR LOCAL) STOPPED THE TRUCK DUE TO A FLUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE OFFICER CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM TO INVESTIGATE THE SUBSTANCE. THE HAZ-MAT TEAM ENTERED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER AND DETERMINED THAT A LID FROM ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAD COME OFF AND CONSEQUENTLY SOME OF THE FLUID HAD SPLASHED AND LEAKED OUT OFF THE CONTAINER.  THE HAZ-MAT TEAM CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND RESEALED THE CONTAINER SO THE LID WOULD NOT COME OFF A SECOND TIME. THE TEAM ALSO CHECKED THE REMAINING DRUMS ON TRAILER WERE SECURED TO ENSURE THEY WOULD NOT COME OFF DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE ON 4/5/2000. DRIVERS ARE NOW REQUIRED TO MAKE SURE THAT ALL CONTAINERS, DRUMS AND BOTTLES, ARE NOT ONLY WRAPPED TO EACH OTHER AND THE PALLET, THEY MUST ALSO BE WRAPPED ON THE TOP TO ENSURE NO LID WOULD BE ABLE TO COME OFF DURING TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON FRIDAY,  APRIL 21, 2000, A TANKER TRUCK OWNED BY GREAT LAKES PETROLEUM CORPORATION LOST CONTROL AND ROLLED OVER AND OFF THE NORTHBOUND EXIT RAMP EMBANKMENT FROM INTERSTATE 94 (EASTBOUND) AT 23 MILE ROAD.  THE TANKER WAS CARRYING UNLEADED GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL.  AFTER SETTING NEAR THE DITCH AT THE FOOT OF THE EMBANKMENT, THE TANKER CAUGHT FIRE.  THE CHESTERFIELD TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO HANDLED THE BLAZE.  MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL (MPC) WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITIES.  THEY CONTAINED THE SPILL AREA WITH BOOMS AND CONSOLIDATED THE LIQUIDS FROM THE SPILL (GASOLINE, DIESEL FUEL, WATER AND FIRE FIGHTING FOAM) INTO A 21,000-GALLON FRAC TANK LOCATED ON THE ADJACENT PARK N' RIDE AREA. CONSOLIDATED ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (CES) WAS RETAINED TO SUPERVISE THE REMOVAL OF IMPACTED SOIL AND TO COLLECT VERIFICATION OF SOIL REMEDIATION SAMPLES FOR ANALYSIS.  ON APRIL 24 AND 25, CES COLLECTED A COMPOSITE SOIL SAMPLE AND A DITCH WATER SAMPLE IN THE SPILL AREA TO CHARACTERIZE THE MEDIA FOR DISPOSAL.  ANALYTICAL RESULTS DICTATED REMOVAL OF THE DITCH WATER AND EXCAVATION OF SOILS FROM THE DITCH AND HILLSIDE ON THE WEST.  THE DITCH WATER WAS CHARACTERIZED AS NON-HAZARDOUS BASED ON ANALYTICAL RESULTS, AND WAS PUMPED AND DISPOSED OF BY USHER OIL COMPANY ON APRIL 27 AND 28.  A TOTAL OF 34,500 GALLONS WAS REMOVED (MANIFESTS ATTACHED).  EXCAVATION OF THE DITCH AND HILLSIDE WAS PERFORMED ON MAY 1 AND 2.  VSR GUIDELINES WERE FOLLOWED TO ESTABLISH A SAMPLING GRID.  CES COLLECTED SAMPLES ON BOTH DAYS (SEE ATTACHED FIGURE FOR LOCATIONS).  ALSO ON MAY 1, CES COLLECTED A WATER/EMULSION SAMPLE FROM THE FRAC TANK ON SITE. LABORATORY RESULTS DICTATED THAT THIS WATER BE HANDLED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. DISPOSAL DOCUMENTATION IS ATTACHED.  SOIL ANALYTICAL RESULTS WERE COMPARED TO GSI AND RESIDENTIAL DIRECT CONTACT CRITERIA.  TWO LOCATIONS HAD A BENZENE DETECTION AND A XYLENE CRITERION EXCEEDANCE (DS-7 AND DS-11, RESPECTIVELY).  ON MAY 8, CES RESAMPLED THE TWO LOCATIONS AFTER ADDITIONAL EXCAVATION WAS PERFORMED.  TABLES OF THE ANALYTICAL RESULTS ARE ATTACHED TO THIS LETTER.  A TOTAL OF 264 CUBIC YARDS OF SOIL WERE HAULED FROM THE SITE AND DISPOSED OF AT WASTE MANAGEMENT'S PINETREE ACRES FACILITY IN LENOX, MICHIGAN (MANIFESTS ATTACHED).

column168: THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION REGARDING A RELEASE FROM A TRUCK IS PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 3750-25-25 (A) (2) (A) - (B) OF THE OHIO ADMINISTRATIVE CODE. THE RELEASE STARTED  AT APPROXIMATELY 6:15 A.M. ON 04/05/00. THE RELEASE CONTINUED UNTIL THE CONTAINER RELEASED ITS CONTENTS WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY 10:00 A.M. THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED BY THE DRIVER AT APPROXIMATELY 6:20 A.M. ON 04/05/00. UPON DETECTION OF THE RELEASE, THE DRIVER MOVED THE TRUCK TO THE BERM OF THE HIGHWAY JUST PAST A REST STOP WHERE THERE WAS PLENTY OF SPACE TO SAFELY PARK THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AT THE LOCATION WHERE THE LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRUCK AND THEN NOTIFIED AUTHORITIES. TURTLE CREEK FIRE DEPARTMENT, HVC'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE RELEASE. SAND WAS PLACED IN THE SMALL DITCH NEXT TO THE ROADWAY TO PREVENT MIGRATION OF THE RELEASE. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL AT AN APPROVED HAZARDOUS WASTE FACILITY. THE NRC REPORT NUMBER IS 525117. THERE WAS NO OHIO EPA SPILL NUMBER ASSIGNED. THE TRUCK INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE IS OPERATED OUT OF HVC INC.'S FACILITY LOCATED AT 46OO DUES DRIVE, CINCINNATI, OHIO 45246. THE RELEASE OCCURRED IN TURTLE CREEK TOWNSHIP WHICH IS LOCATED IN WARREN COUNTY. THE RELEASE FROM THE TRUCK OCCURRED AT THE 34 MILE MARKER OF I-71 NORTHBOUND BERM JUST NORTH OF THE REST STOP. THE PRODUCT RELEASED WAS 37% FORMALDEHYDE. THE CAS NUMBER IS 50-00-0. THE ENVIRONMENTAL MEDIA IMPACTED WAS THE SOIL NEXT TO THE BERM. APPROXIMATELY A 300 FT2  AREA OF SOIL WAS INVOLVED. NO WATER SOURCES OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED. NO MONITORING WAS PERFORMED DURING THE RELEASE. ALL CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES WERE PERFORMED WITH SCBA EQUIPMENT. THE WIND WAS FROM THE SOUTH AND WAS INITIALLY CALM, LATER INCREASING TO 5-10 KNOTS. ALL PERSONNEL WERE KEPT UPWIND OF THE RELEASE. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINER(TOTE) WAS RELEASED, APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS. THE FREE LIQUID IN THE TRUCK WAS TREATED WITH SODIUM METABISULFITE AND ABSORBED WITH SODIUM SULFATE.  THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN AN CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL. SAND WAS PLACED IN A SWALLOW DITCH  NEXT TO THE RELEASE AREA TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE TO AS SMALL OF AN AREA AS POSSIBLE. SODIUM METABISULFITE WAS ADDED TO THE FREE LIQUID TO REDUCE THE ODOR OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE. THE FOLLOWING IS A CHRONOLOGICAL SUMMARY OF THE INCIDENT THAT OCCURRED ON 4/05/00: 6:20 A.M. THE DRIVER PULLS OVER TO PERFORM TIRE CHECK AND NOTICES A LITTLE DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER PULLS THE TRAILER UP APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS, PLACES ABSORBENT PILLOWS AROUND DRIPPING LIQUID AND CALLS HVC DISPATCH. 6:30 A.M.  THE OHIO STATE HIGHWAY PATROL IS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE BY HVC PERSONNEL. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT IS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDS. 6:50 A.M. HVC INC. CONTACTS LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND REQUESTS THEM TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. HVC'S RESPONSE TEAM IS ENROUTE

column168: THIS WAS A PERSONAL SHIPMENT. THE SHIPPER WENT TO SOME VERY SERIOUS LENGTHS TO PORTRAY THE SHIPPER AS DR. ANDERSON WHEN IT WAS SOMEONE WHO GAVE US THE NAME OF SAMANTHA ANDERSON. THIS MISS ANDERSON SET UP A FEDEX ACCOUNT # THE DAY BEFORE THE SHIPMENT WENT OUT. I SPOKE TO DR. ANDERSON WHO ADVISED HE HAD NO FEDEX ACCOUNT NUMBER. HE COULD HAVE BEEN LYING BUT MY EXPERIENCE LEADS ME TO BELIEVE OTHERWISE. WE DELIVERED THE REMAINING 18 BOXES BEFORE I DISCOVERED THE HIDDEN SHIPMENT. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY SA ANDREW JOHNSON, FAA-MEM. I ONLY LEFT MESSAGES FOR THE SHIPPER, THEY WERE NEVER RETURNED. THE BOX CONTAINED SEVERAL UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THE BOX HAD NO MARKING, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS TO OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURRED. THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN IT WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING. THIS HAD THE EFFECT OF PUNCTURING BOTH THE INNER AND OUTER UNITS ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER/RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: FILE 2030 F & D SHIPPER: JOE ALBERT, AIR WAYBILL # YYZ 40118868576 DSM 6 E, THIS IS A HIDDEN DISCREPANCY. ON OPERATIONS DATE 04/03/2000. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, BRUCE SHILTZ AND MIKE COOK WERE CALLED TO INVESTIGATE ODOR IN THE LOWER COMPARTMENT (BELLY 2) OF AN AIRBORNE EXPRESS DC-9. AIRCRAFT PARKED AT GATE A-34 LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH, 45177. UPON ARRIVAL THE HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN MET WITH PART TIME RAMP EMPLOYEE LANCE SMALTZ WHO NOTICED AND REPORTED THE ODOR TO RAMP SUPERVISOR, PAUL GROPPENBACHER WHO CALLED IN THE ODOR TO THE SPILL TEAM. P/T HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN BRUCE SHILTZ INQUIRED TO MR. SMALTZ IF HE NEEDED ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION, AND HE ADVISED HE DID NOT.P/T HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN , BRUCE SHILTZ AND MIKE COOK DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE GEAR AND ENTERED THE LOWER COMPARTMENT (BELLY 2) OF THE AIRCRAFT AND BEGAN SEARCHING FOR THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. THE SPILL TEAM FOUND A PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF A WHITE SUBSTANCE AND PLACED IT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND REMOVED IT FROM THE COMPARTMENT. THE SPILL TEAM LOOKED FOR HAZARDOUS MARKINGS, LABELS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE BUT DID NOT FIND ANY. THE ONLY MARKINGS AND ATTACHMENTS WERE AS FOLLOWS: ON TOP OF THE PACKAGE WERE TWO PUROLATOR COURIER LABELS, A ROUTING DESTINATION STICKER (DSMC 6-C) AND A ORIGIN STICKER (YYZ). ON SIDE 1 OF THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION ARE THE WORDS IN FRENCH: PEINTURE CRAINT LE GEL AND ORIENTATION ARROWS. SIDE TWO WAS THE FOLLOWING: 4 X 3.78L. ON SIDE THREE WAS THE PUROLATOR COURIER AIR WAYBILL WHICH PARTIALLY OBSCURED SOME MARKINGS SHOWN HERE: PA AND KEEP FR,ALL THE REST OF THE WORDS ARE OBSCURED. ALSO ON THIS SIDE WAS ORIENTATION ARROWS. SIDE FOUR HAD TWO PUROLATOR LABELS AND THE SHIPPER, JOE ALBERT ADDRESS LABEL. BOTTOM: ALL INFORMATION SUCH AS THE PACKAGE MANUFACTURE SEAL WAS UNOBTAINABLE DUE TO THE LEAKING PRODUCT. UPON OPENING THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION THE FOLLOWING CONTENTS WERE DISCOVERED: 2 X 1 GALLON METAL CANS EACH MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWS : PAINT RELATED MATERIAL, UN1283, BOTH LABELED FLAMMABLE LIQUID, 1 OF WHICH LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES OF WHITE PAINT. BOTH OF THE 1 GALLON METAL CAN WERE ALSO MARKED PART A. ALSO FOUND IN THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION WERE 3 X 1 QUART METAL CANS 2 OF WHICH WERE MARKED ANY PART AND OTHER MARKINGS OR LABELS, THE THIRD 1 QUART CAN APPEARED TO HAVE HAD MARKINGS BUT WERE ILLEGIBLE DUE TO THE LEAKING PAINT. FURTHER DISCOVERED WAS A 1 X 1 PINT METAL CAN THAT DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKING OR LABELS BUT HALF OF THE UNKNOWN PRODUCT LEAKED OUT. FINALLY THERE WAS AN 8 TO 10 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE FOUND THAT ALSO HAD NO MARKINGS TO INDICATE WHAT IT CONTAINED. THIS PLASTIC RECEPTACLE DID NOT LEAK. THE ABOVE SHIPMENT WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT BUILDING AND REPACKED INTO A UN 1A1 STEEL DRUM, AND PLACED INTO OUT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTILL IT COULD BE INVESTIGATED BY FAA.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY OCCURRED. THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN IT WAS INADVERTENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING. THIS HAS THE EFFECT OF CAUSING THE LID SEAL ON THE INNER UNIT TO FAIL ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. DURING THE CLEAN UP PROCESS THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A POLYURETHANE PAINT. MARKINGS ON THE LABEL OF THIS UNIT CLEARLY INDICATED THE PAINT TO BE FLAMMABLE. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE SURFACE OF THE OUTER BOX NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION. PHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT INO LLANES FAA/MIA/CAFSO AT 07:55 (CST) ON 04/14/2000.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED. THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLERS NOTICED STRONG ODORS COMING FROM THE CONTAINER. THE UNIT WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL VARIOUS TYPES OF CLOTHING AND HOUSEHOLD ITEMS. ALSO INCLUDED WAS AN AEROSOL CAN SPRAY STARCH. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR THE DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION. PHONE CONTACT WAS MADE WITH SPECIAL AGENT ANDY HUBER/FAA/IND/CAFSO ON 04/17/2000. OF SPECIAL NOTE HERE IS THAT ALTHOUGH THE AIRBILL INDICATES INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA AS THE ORIGIN THE SHIPPING RECORD WILL SHOW THAT THIS ITEM ACTUALLY ORIGINATED IN THE WASHINGTON, DC AREA AND DID TRANSIT BY AIR TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: FILE 2027 F & D, SHPR:  BBLLC, AWB # PRW 2959358732ELA .  ON 04/02/2000 AT 11:33 ON ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING A OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT:  ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO  45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN RANDY WILLIAMS DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A GREEN "C"  CONTAINER CONTAINING SEVERAL PIECES OF FREIGHT.  ONE OF THE PIECES OF FREIGHT WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR.  HE REMOVED THE BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS EMITTING THE ODOR FROM THE "C" CONTAINER AND BEGAN INSPECTION.  HE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND IT TO CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY 120 GLASS BOTTLES OF FINGER NAIL POLISH 10 OF WHICH WERE BROKEN.  THESE BROKEN BOTTLES OF NAIL POLISH WERE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  HE REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO  THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX AND PLACED IT INSIDE OF 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH  ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  HE PLACED THE BAGGED BOX. INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THERE WAS 1 EMPLOYEE WHO NOTICED THE ODOR, SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND SHE RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED FOR HER.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE 1200.

column168: ON 4/25/00 OUR VEHICLE WAS GOING SOUTH ON#417 AND GOLDENROD ROAD, ORLANDO FLORIDA.  DRIVER STATES THE BRAKES LOCKED UP, HE OVER CORRECTED LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE & IT ROLLED TWICE. A 2 1/4 "VALVE PULLED OUT IN THE CENTER BACK AREA OF TRUCK RELEASING.  1200 _ 1500 GALLONS OF PROPANE IN LIQUID FORM WHICH DISSIPATED IMMEDIATELY. ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL, WHO WERE ON SITE, ADVISED AREA WAS CLEANED UP TO THEIR SATISFACTION.  AIR PORT PERSONNEL SPRAYED THE AREA WITH FOAM.  THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED FROM SCENE.  THE ROAD AS CLOSED FOR 6 HOURS.  DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO FLORIDA EST HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE. DRIVER SUSTAINED SLIGHT LACERATIONS ON ARM FROM BROKEN GLASS, SCRAPE TO STOMACH AREA DUE TO SEATBELT, BUMP ON LEG CAUSED BY SEAT BELT. DRIVER WAS OFF WORK 4-26-00 THROUGH 4-28-00, RETURNED TO WORK 5-1-00.  REPORTED TO FLORIDA WARNING POINT OUR INCIDENT #SWP0004251742.  REPORTED TO NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, MR. LORECK, INCIDENT #527067.

THIS DUFFEL BAG WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A NOTICEABLE ODOR WHEN IT ARRIVED AT THEIR FACILITY.  UPSON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE TO FIND THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO  METAL 4 OZ CANS OF A LEATHER LUSTER BOOT POLISH WERE INSIDE THE DUFFEL BAG, ONE OF WHICH HAD LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT.  I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE LEAKAGE AND BEGAN TO RESEARCH THE PRODUCT VIA THE INTERNET FOR SOME PRODUCT INFORMATION.  I WAS ABLE TO CONTACT THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT AND RECEIVED A FAX COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS), WHICH SHOWED THE PRODUCT TO HAVE A FLASH  POINT OF 10-19 DEGREES FARENHEIT.  THE GI DUFFEL BAG WAS NOT LABELED AND MARKED TO DECLARE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS AND THEIR WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK FOR THE SHIPMENT.  I CONTACTED JANA NICASTRO OF THE ANC/CASFO TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS LATER RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE AFTER THE INVESTIGATION WAS COMPLETED.

THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED IN COMPLIANCE WITH 49 CFR.  THIS INCIDENT IS OR MAY BE SUBJECT TO FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY AMERICAN AIRLINES. THIS REPORT IS NOT TO BE CONSTRUED AS OFFICIAL DETERMINATION OF THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.  AA FREIGHT CONTAINING INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCES WAS FOUND ON TAXI WAY RAMP BY GATE E 32.  THE BOX APPARENTLY FELL FROM A BAGGAGE CART WHILE BEING TRANSPORTED ON THE GROUND.  THE BOX DID RECEIVE SOME DAMAGE BUT IT IS UNCERTAIN IF DAMAGE WAS CAUSED BY THE FALL OR IF STRUCK BY A VEHICLE.  FREIGHT WAS RECOVERED AND DESTROYED BY THE LOCAL HEALTH DEPARTMENT (SEE ATTACHED).  4 EMPLOYEES RECEIVED ANTIBODICS AS A PRECAUTION.  DOCTOR'S DO NOT BELIEVE EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED SINCE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTION WAS WORN DURING HANDLING.  INCIDENT CAUSED NO CHANGE IN FLIGHT SCHEDULES.

WHILE UNLOADING FLT 3752.  FLEET SERVICE CLERKS NOTICED STRONG FUEL ODOR EMANATING FROM THE CARGO HOLD.  THEY DISCOVERED TWO BAGS SOAKED WITH THE DIESEL FUEL.  THE BAGS WERE TRANSFERRED TO THE BAGROOM. ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR AND PASSENGER WERE CONTACTED.  E.C. ADVISED PASSENGER THAT THE BAG COULD NOT BE TRANSPORTED.  AFTER AIRCRAFT WAS UNLOADED A 3" PUDDLE OF DIESEL FUEL REMAINED ON THE FLOOR OF THE CARGO COMPARTMENT.  PUDDLE WAS CLEANED UP BY COMPANY PERSONNEL.  AIRCRAFT RETURNED TO SERVICE.

THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0144.

FILE 2038 F&D, SHIPPER EQUIFAX, AWB#LEK 1205411620GWD.  ON 04/28/00 AT 0125 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING C OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIAN PAUL SCHMIDT DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING A LIQUID.  HE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND IT TO CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING REGULATED MATERIAL;  1 x 14.2 OUNCE METAL SPRAY CAN OF OPTIMUM CARE BODY & SHINE, CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE .  THERE WERE OTHER NON REGULATED MATERIALS IN THIS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO IDENTIFY IT AS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  HE REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE BOX AND PLACED THE BOX INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. HE PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0142.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE LATC. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS BEING MOVED FROM THE CITY OF INDUSTRY INTERMODAL FACILITY AND BEING DELIVERED TO THE LATC FOR RELOADING AND FURTHER RAIL MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION. THE CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS WHILE BEING CHECKED INTO THE LATC AND WAS MOVED TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LATC AND NOTED A GREEN LIQUID SUBSTANCE DRIPPING FROM THE REAR DOORS. UPON OPENING THE DOORS, OBSERVED THE LADING TO BE BAGS OF MIRACLE GROW PLANT FOOD. THE 25 POUND BAGS WERE STACKED ON PALLETS AND STRETCH WRAPPED. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WHICH IS NOT APPROVED FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON RAIL. SEVERAL OF THE PALLETS HAD SHIFTED CAUSING THE BAGS TO SHIFT AGAINST THE STRETCH WRAP AND EVENTUALLY TOPPLE OFF THE PALLETS. AT LEAST 5 BAGS WERE NOTED TORN OPEN ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO MIX WITH MOISTURE ON THE FLOORING. IT IS PRESUMED THIS MATERIAL WAS LOADED WHILE IT WAS RAINING TO ACCUMULATE THE MOISTURE ON THE FLOORING, AS NO DEFECTS WERE NOTED TO THE CONTAINER ROOF. AS THE LEAKING MOISTURE WAS MINIMAL, THE CONTAINER WAS ALLOWED TO SIT UNTIL THE FOLLOWING MORNING WHEN THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED TO HAVE THE LADING REWORKED. ONCE THE PALLETS WERE RECOOPED, REWRAPPED, AND PROPERLY SECURED THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

MGR. C.T.S. R. SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD FORCES AT HINKLE OF A TANK CAR NATX 37069 THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP. MR. SLOANE RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE LIQUID LINE VALVE FLANGE. MR SLOANE SECURED THE FLANGE BOLTS AND RELEASED THE CAR.

MR STOCKSDALE CALLED MGR WILDER BACK AND INFORMED HIM THAT SOO LINES CONTRACTOR HAD TIGHTENED TWO (2) MANWAY COVER BOLTS WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE 1/2 TURN LOOSE.

column168: ON 4/18/00 W.M. SEABAUGH MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED IN REFERENCE TO A CHLORINE LIKE ODOR REPORTEDLY NOTED ALONG TRACK #204, UPRR YARD NORTH LITTLE ROCK, AR. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY FORCES REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER ON THE INBOUND IEWLBB-02 TRACK 805. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND INSPECTED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WHILE IT WAS STILL SITUATED ON THE RAILCAR. THE LEAK WAS 1 DROP PER SECOND AND COMING FROM THE CENTER FLOOR AREA OF THE TOP CONTAINER. THE TOP CONTAINER A 40 FOOT CAN WAS ON TOP OF 2 20 FOOT CONTAINERS POSITIONED IN THE WELL OF THE DOUBLE STACK CAR, FEC 4498. TO FACILITATE INSPECTION OF THE LADING, THE TOP CONTAINER WAS REMOVED, DIAPERED AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE 2 BOTTOM CONTAINERS WERE ALSO REMOVED AND PLACED CURB SIDE AT THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE THEY COULD BE CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE. THE RAILCAR WAS THEN CLEANED TO FACILITATE THE RELOADING OPERATION.UPON OPENING THE LEAKING CONTAINER NOTED THE LADING TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS. THE BOTTOM TIER CONSISTED OF 80 DRUMS HELD IN PLACE WITH TY-GARD. THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS AT THE DOOR CONSISTED OF A ROW OF 4 DRUMS WHICH IS NOT A APPROVED LOADING PROTOCOL WITH THE USE OF THE TY-GARD RESTRAINT SYSTEM. THE TOP TIER OF DRUMS HAD BEEN LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER ALSO UTILIZING THE TY-GARD. 4 DRUMS WERE LAYING ON THEIR SIDES AND THE TY-GARD WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME OF THE INITIAL INSPECTION. AS THE LADING WAS ACTIVELY LEAKING IT WAS DECIDED TO REMOVE THE DRUMS AND LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. UPON ENTERING THE CONTAINER TO ADDRESS THE TOPPLED DRUMS IT WAS NOTED THAT THE TY-GARD MATERIALS WAS UNDER THE DRUMS THAT HAD FALLEN OVER. IT APPEARS THAT THE MATERIAL HAD TORN AWAY FROM THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE WALL  ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO TOPPLE. THE DRUMS WERE RIGHTED AND 2 WERE FOUND TO BE EMPTY. THE 2 EMPTY DRUMS SUSTAINED WEAR AT THE TOP AND BOTTOM ROLLING HOOPS FROM ROCKING BACK AND FORTH ON TOP OF THE DRUMS FROM THE LOWER TIER. A THIRD DRUM WAS RIGHTED AND FOUND TO HAVE THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP DAMAGED IN THE SAME MANNER. THIS DRUM HAD LOST HALF OF IT'S CONTENTS. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR SECUREMENT. THE FORTH DRUM WAS RIGHTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE, HOWEVER SUSTAINED HEAVY WEAR DAMAGE TO THE TOP AND BOTTOM ROLLING HOOPS. 2 DRUMS FROM THE BOTTOM TIER WERE FOUND TO HAVE 18 INCH OPENINGS IN THE TOPS FROM THE TOPPLED DRUMS ROLLING BACK AND FORTH ACROSS THEM. IT APPEARED THAT NO PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THESE DRUMS. THE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO OVERPACKS FOR SECUREMENT. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE RE MOVED AND INSPECTED FOR DAMAGE. NO ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING, HOWEVER DUE TO THE LADING SHIFTING WHILE IN TRANSIT A TOTAL OF 28 DRUMS SUSTAINED DAMAGE AND WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE LOADED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. THE 2 BOTTOM CONTAINERS, CBHU 309514 AND CBHU 42764 WERE CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND ALSO RELEASED. THE DAMAGED DRUMS WILL BE RET

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. DEVELOPED MTO LINDA SEAFAIR WAS ON SITE WITH THE LOS ANGELES CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO HAD RESPONDED TO A TRAIN STOPPED OUTSIDE THE LATC. A CITIZEN NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE ABOVE CONTAINER WHILE ON THE TRAIN AND CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. AS THERE WAS NO SAFETY WAY TO INSPECT THE CONTAINER WHILE ON THE TRAIN IT WAS APPROVED MOVING THE TRAIN INTO THE LATC WHERE THE CONTAINER COULD BE REMOVED WITH THE PROPER INTERMODAL HANDLING EQUIPMENT. ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS OFF THE FLAT CAR IT WAS MOVED TO THE DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LATC AND OBTAINED THE PAPERWORK ON THE CONTAINER, WHICH SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE GENERAL FREIGHT, EVEN THOUGH THE CAN WAS PLACARDED BOTH FLAMMABLE AND CORROSIVE. FIELD TESTING OF THE LEAKING PRODUCT SHOWED NEUTRAL SIGNS OF PH, AND DID NOT READILY BURN. CSX INTERMODAL WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO FAX THE PROPER HAZARD INFORMATION, AND WHEN RECEIVED, SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE A SMALL QUANTITY OF CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, AND APPROXIMATELY 2000 POUNDS OF FLAMMABLES. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER,  NOTED THE CONTENTS TO BE MIXED FREIGHT IN BAGS, BOXES AND PAILS. A PALLET CONTAINING 50 POUND BAGS OF GROUT POWDER WAS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD,  AND THE STRETCH WRAP HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE BAGS TO TOPPLE. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING OBSERVED WHICH IS NOT AN APPROVED METHOD OF TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES ON RAIL. FURTHER INTO THE LOAD, NUMEROUS 5 GALLONS PAILS WERE NOTED TO HAVE TOPPLED OFF OF THE PALLETS THEY HAD BEEN LOADED ON. ALL OF THE LADING HAD TO BE REMOVED BY HAND TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINERS. WHILE REMOVING THE LADING DEVELOPED A MAJORITY OF LEAKING MATERIAL WAS FROM 2 DAMAGE POLY PAILS THAT CONTAINED A SPRAY DECK RESIN,  A NONREGULATED PRODUCT. THE PAILS HAD BEEN CRUSHED WHEN THEY TOPPLED OFF THE PALLET. 3 ADDITIONAL PAILS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE REMOVING THE LADING, WHICH WERE PART OF THE REGULATED COMMODITIES. 2 WERE LEAKING FROM THE SIDES WHERE THEY HAD BEEN ABRADED BY THE ADJACENT PAILS. 1 LEAKED FROM THE SIDE WHERE THE HANDLES ATTACHES TO THE PAIL. LESS THAN 2-3 GALLONS WAS LOST FROM THESE PAILS. THEY WERE PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WAS RELEASED TO CSX FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR TO THE CONTAMINATED FLOORING. THE REMAINING FREIGHT WAS PICKED UP BY A LOCAL VENDOR FOR RECOOPING AND FORWARDING ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. DIALOG WITH THE SHIPPER CONTINUES WITH THE INITIAL RESPONSE AND WASTE ISSUES.

ON OR ABOUT MARCH 19, 2000 WHILE AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD YARD AT LIVONIA, LOUISIANA TANK CAR GATX 11845 WAS FOUND TO BE OVERLOADED, BY WEIGHT NOT VOLUME. THE SHIPPER SAFETY KLEEN WAS NOTIFIED TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A REDUCTION. UNION PACIFIC PLACED THE CAR ON HOLD AT LIVONIA YARD. ON OR ABOUT 4/4/2000 SAFETY KLEEN REMOVED A SAMPLE FROM THE CAR WHILE IT WAS AWAITING LOAD REDUCTION AT LIVONIA YARD FOR LAB ANALYSIS.ON TUESDAY 4/4/2000 UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS T.M. ROBINSON OBSERVED THE TANK CAR ON TRACK 105 AT LIVONIA YARD AND FOUND THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN LEAKING  PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE. ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT HALF OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE. IN ADDITION A LENGTH OF RUBBER AIR HOSE HAD BEEN SLIT AND INSTALLED AS A MAKE SHIFT GASKET FOR THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE SHIPPER UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. TROOPER C.J. LANOUE LSP AND MR H TYLER GINN L-DEQ RESPONDED TO MONITOR THE SITUATION. MR. OVIDE DESOTO PROJECT MANAGER FOR SAFETY KLEEN RESPONDED ALONG WITH ONE TECHNICIAN TO SECURE THE CAR AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE THAT WAS ON THE CAR. ON WEDNESDAY 4/19/2000, MR DESOTO RETURNED TO THE LIVONIA YARD ALONG WITH A VACUUM TRUCK AND REDUCED THE TANK CAR LOAD APPROXIMATELY 2500 GALLONS WITH OUT INCIDENT. MR DESOTO THEN RESECURED THE CAR FOR SHIPMENT.

ON 04182000 S/A HAZMAT C ZERWICK NOTIFIED RMCC THAT HE NOTICED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM A BULKTAINER IN MILLER YARD, DALLAS, TX. ZERWICK ASKED RMCC TO CONTACT MGR CTS M. KElly. UPON CONTACT WITH KELLY, ZERWICK ADVISED THAT HE COULD SMELL A STRONG ODOR NEAR THE CAR BUT DID NOT CLIMB ON THE CAR TO LOCATE WERE IT WAS COMING FROM. UPON ARRIVING AT THE SCENE KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THERE WAS A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM UNDER THE MANWAY COVER ON THE TOP OF THE CAR. KELLY TIGHTENED THE EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS AND THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED (REPORT#04182000037) AND KELLY REQUESTED THAT HE BE CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER. THE BULKTAINER WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS BEING PICKED UP AND CHECKED OUT OF THE TERMINAL WHEN THE DRAYMAN NOTICED A LIQUID SUBSTANCE LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING NEAR THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND INSPECTED THE 20 CONTAINER NOTING A SMALL POOL OF PRODUCT (LESS THAN ONE PINT) HAD ACCUMULATED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA UNDER THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER.THERE WAS A SLIGHT ODOR TO THE LIQUID INDICATING IT WAS PRODUCT FROM THE MATERIAL BEING SHIPPED. SEAL CC17011 WAS REMOVED AND THE REAR DOORS OPENED TO INSPECT THE LADING, THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS DOUBLE STACKED PLYWOOD BILEVEL SEPARATION AND SECURE THE PLACE WITH A TY-PATCH. THE BOTTOM TIER OF DRUMS HAD SHIFTED SLIGHTLY ON THE RIGHT SIDE AS THE DRUMS ON THE LAST ROW AND THE SECOND LAST ROW WERE SET OFF BY APPROXIMATELY 4 INCHES. THE SHIPPER HAD PROPERLY BAYED OUT THE DRUMS IN THE LOADING PROTOCOL BY PLACING A ROW OF 3 DRUMS AT THE MID POINT AND AT THE REAR ROW OF THE LOAD. THE APPLICATION OF THE TY-PATCH WAS SOMEWHAT IN CONFORMANCE WITH THE PROPER APPLICATION, HOWEVER THERE ARE TWO AREAS THAT SHOULD BE REVISITED AND ADDRESSED. WHEN WRAPPING AND APPLYING THE PATCH AT THE REAR OF THE LADING THE STRIPS SHOULD REMAIN HORIZONTAL TO THE FLOOR AND NOT TAPER DOWN. BOTH STRIPS ON BOTH TIERS  WERE TAPERED DOWN FROM WHERE THEY WERE ATTACHED TO THE SIDE WALL TO WHERE THEY WRAPPED AROUND THE DRUMS AT THE REAR. THERE WAS MINIMUM OF 6 INCHES DIFFERENCE IN THE HEIGHT OF MATERIAL FROM THE SIDE WALLS AND THE REAR AREA WHERE THE PATCH WAS APPLIED.THIS DOES NOT ALLOW THE MATERIAL TO REMAIN ON PLANE AND REDUCE THE EFFICIENCY OF THE MATERIAL. ALSO THE PATCH PIECE NEEDS TO BE FULLY APPLIED TO THE SIDE WALL PIECES. ON THE LOWER STRIP FROM THE TOP TIER AND THE LOWER STRIP FROM THE BOTTOM TIER BOTH PATCH PIECES WERE OFF BY AT LEAST 6 INCHES AND WOUND UP BEING ADHEARED TO THE DRUMS RATHER THAN FULLY ADHEARED TO THE SIDE WALL STRIP OF THE TY-PATCH. THIS ALSO REDUCES THE EFFICIENCY OF THE MATERIAL TO PROPERLY SECURE THE LADING. DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS OF THE DRUMS TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PLYWOOD SHEETING PLACED ON THE FLOOR AND UTILIZED FOR THE BILEVEL SEPARATION WERE CUT TOO SHORT. THERE WERE GAPS TOWARDS THE SIDES OF THE CONTAINER THAT WERE 2-3 INCHES. THIS SHORT CUTTING OF THE PLYWOOD ALLOWS 2-3 INCHES OF THE DRUMS TO HANG OVER THE SIDES OF THE PLYWOOD AND CREATES AN UNEVEN SURFACE FOR THE DRUMS TO REST ON. THIS CREATES A STRESS ON THE BOTTOM CHIMES OF THE DRUMS AND WILL EVENTUALLY CAUSE THE DRUMS TO FAIL. IN THE CASE OF THE LAST ROW 3 DRUMS ON THE TOP TIER THE DRUM ON THE LEFT SIDE WAS ONLY PARTIALLY RESTING ON THE PLYWOOD AND A FULL ONE THIRD OF THE DRUM HAD NO SUPPORT AT ALL. column168: ON 042700 AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 P.M. MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION GEOFFREY REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING. UPON ARRIVAL REEDER FOUND THE CAR LEAKING A STEADY STREAM FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. REEDER TIGHTENED THE VALVE AND STOPPED THE LEAK. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN JEFFERY KIDDER DONNED PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND SEVERAL PIECES OF FREIGHT LOCATED ON THE SLIDE AREA.  ONE OF THESE PLACES WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR.  HE REMOVED THE BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX FROM THE SLIDE AREA AND BEGAN INSPECTION.  HE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING ITEMS: 3 - 1 GI METAL PAINT TYPE CANS LABLED WOOD STAIN FLAMMABLE WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS OF CLOSURE, 1 - 1PT METAL PAINT TYPE CAN ALL LABELING OBSCURED. 1 OF THE 1GL CONTAINERS WAS LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 1 PT FROM AN OPEN CLOSURE.  THIS WAS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKAGE AND THE ODOR.  HE REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. HE PLACED THE BAGGED BOX INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT SORT AREA SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED AND WASHED WITH SOAP AND WATER BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THERE WAS 1 EMPLOYEE WHO NOTICED THE ODOR, HE WAS ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND HE RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED FOR THE 1 EMPLOYEE.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WORE CLEAR OF SCENE 1027.

column168: JERMEY GENTRY TRUCK DRIVER CALLED OFFICE AT 12:30 PM SAID HE ROLLED TRUCK AT PRAIRIE CREEK IN RICHARDSON TEXAS. I CALLED CACTUS ENVIRONMENTAL FOR CLEAN UP AND FIRE DEPT CITY OF RICHARDSON. NO ONE WAS HURT ALL PEOPLE INVOLVED DID A PROFESSIONAL JOB I HAVE PICTURE ON WALL OF INCIDENT TO REMIND ALL DRIVER TO BE SAFE AND SLOW DOWN. ON THE AFTERNOON OF APRIL 24, 2000 AT 3000-GALLON FUEL TRUCK ROLLED OVER IN THE 2600 BLOCK OF PRAIRIE CREEK WEST IN RICHARDSON, TEXAS. SUBSEQUENT TO ROLL OVER APPROXIMATELY 732-GALLONS OF FUEL WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE INCLUDED 690-GALLONS OF LOW SULFUR DIESEL, 12-GALLONS OF HIGH SULFUR DIESEL AND 30-GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE. THE TRUCK CAME TO REST ON THE CURB OF THE  PARKING LOT ADJACENT TO A SMALL CITY PARK. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED DOWN THE CURB INTO A STORM DRAIN THAT FED INTO THE CREEK THE PRODUCT ALSO CONTAMINATED A LARGE AREA OF SOIL IN THE PARK. THE AREA OF THE PARK THAT WAS CONTAMINATED INCLUDED A GROVE OF LARGE TREES. THE TREES ROOTS AND DRY SOIL CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SEEP DEEPER INTO THE SOIL THEN WOULD BE EXPECTED. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RICHARDSON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD COMMAND. ALSO ON SCENE WAS DALLAS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ-MAT UNIT (HAZ-MAT 4), DALLAS STORM WATER REPRESENTATIVE, TNRCC REPRESENTATIVE, AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE RICHARDSON HEALTH DEPARTMENT. LATER IN THE DAY A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE EPA ARRIVED ON SCENE. THE CONTACT FOR THE CITY OF RICHARDSON WAS BILL ALSUP FROM THE HEALTH DEPARTMENT. THE PHONE NUMBER FOR THE CITY OF RICHARDSON HEALTH DEPARTMENT IS 972-238-4179.
